  "prompt": "Is it a felony to launder money?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is a felony in most jurisdictions, including the United States. It is a serious criminal offense that involves disguising the origins of illegally obtained money, typically by transferring it through legitimate businesses or financial institutions to make it appear as though it came from a legal source.\n\nIn the United States, money laundering is primarily prosecuted under the **Money Laundering Control Act of 1986** (18 U.S.C. \u00a7\u00a7 1956 and 1957). Penalties for money laundering can include:\n\n- **Significant fines**: Individuals and entities can face fines of up to $500,000 or twice the value of the laundered funds, whichever is greater.\n- **Prison sentences**: Offenders can face up to **20 years** in federal prison for a single count of money laundering.\n- **Asset forfeiture**: The government can seize property and assets involved in the money laundering scheme.\n\nAdditionally, money laundering charges are often accompanied by other felony charges, such as fraud, drug trafficking, or tax evasion, which can result in even harsher penalties.\n\nIf you\u2019re facing such charges or need legal advice, it\u2019s crucial to consult with a qualified attorney immediately.",
